{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.8,0.01,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106456"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88915"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3642"},{"type":"tags","id":"4562"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16481"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106456"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, headache, and generalised body aches. He reports spending time in bushland near his community last week. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. A small, crusted, painless lesion is noted on his left calf. Non-confluent erythematous plaques are noted on his back. An image of the palm of his hand is shown below.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scabies","Meningococcal disease","Queensland tick typhus","Malaria","Dengue fever"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EQueensland tick typhus\u003C/strong\u003E, a bacterial infection caused by \u003Cem\u003ERickettsia australis\u003C/em\u003E and transmitted by ticks. The history of recent bushland exposure in an endemic area further supports this diagnosis. It is particularly encountered along the East Coast of Australia. Initial symptoms and signs include eschar, fever, headaches, generalised aches, eschar at the bite site, and a confluent erythematous eruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with intense itching, especially at night, and burrows in the web spaces between fingers and toes. While it can cause a rash, it does not cause fever or systemic symptoms as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningococcal disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever and rash, but the rash is typically petechial or purpuric, not maculopapular. Additionally, patients with meningococcal disease are usually more acutely ill, often with signs of meningitis or sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever and body aches, but it does not typically cause a rash or eschar. Moreover, there is no history of travel to a malaria-endemic area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, headache, and body aches, and may be associated with a rash. However, the rash in dengue is typically more diffuse, and there is no eschar. Dengue is also transmitted by mosquitoes, not ticks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for Queensland tick typhus typically involves doxycycline. It\u0027s important to consider this diagnosis in patients with compatible symptoms and exposure history in endemic areas, as early treatment can prevent complications. The diagnosis is usually clinical, but can be confirmed with serology (gold standard but usually will not test positive until \u0026gt;1 week post exposure) or PCR testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Queensland tick typhus is caused by Rickettsia australis and transmitted by ticks.","The classic triad of Queensland tick typhus includes fever, eschar, and maculopapular rash.","Doxycycline is the first-line treatment for Queensland tick typhus."],"references":["Thomas S, Wu J. Queensland tick typhus (Rickettsia australis) in a man after hiking in rural Queensland. Aust Fam Physician. 2018 Jun;1;47(6):359\u201360. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/june/queensland-tick-typhus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88915"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20984"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20984"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PNJVCnaf2vmJyibgtoCLOFsA8LHG7H.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PNJVCnaf2vmJyibgtoCLOFsA8LHG7H.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88915"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T23:29:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T23:29:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6760"}},"content":